335
00:27:29.524 --> 00:27:30.608
Here you go, sir.

336
00:27:30.691 --> 00:27:32.693
More Lydia's life
than mine, sir.

337
00:27:34.153 --> 00:27:35.446
She's in the Navy, you see.

338
00:27:36.405 --> 00:27:37.573
What, as a cook?

339
00:27:38.407 --> 00:27:41.619
Or some kind of seagoing
secretary or...

340
00:27:41.702 --> 00:27:44.580
Oh, no, sir. She's the captain
of a nuclear submarine.

341
00:27:45.915 --> 00:27:47.250
Oh, right.
Hmm.

342
00:27:49.669 --> 00:27:52.421
Do you think we should get
some petrol for the Aston, sir?

343
00:27:53.881 --> 00:27:58.135
No. An Aston Martin is
surprisingly economical, Bough.

344
00:28:00.179 --> 00:28:03.182
Besides, it looks like
we're in business.

345
00:28:17.238 --> 00:28:18.406
Come on.

346
00:28:25.621 --> 00:28:27.582
Looks like
an electric car, sir.

347
00:28:27.665 --> 00:28:30.126
Yes, and sounds like
a nose hair trimmer.

348
00:28:32.253 --> 00:28:33.838
A bunch
of triple-A batteries

349
00:28:33.921 --> 00:28:36.549
is no match for old-fashioned
British horsepower.

350
00:28:58.070 --> 00:29:01.449
Look at her cornering. Seems
so effortless, doesn't it, sir?

351
00:29:40.821 --> 00:29:42.406
Arm the missile.

352
00:29:42.490 --> 00:29:43.616
The what?

353
00:29:43.699 --> 00:29:45.952
The missile, Bough, the one
with the tear gas warhead.

354
00:29:46.035 --> 00:29:48.579
But they're just cyclists,
sir. We'll get past in a minute.

355
00:29:48.663 --> 00:29:49.830
They're French cyclists,
Bough,

356
00:29:49.956 --> 00:29:52.667
and they're obstructing
Her Majesty's Secret Service.

357
00:30:00.508 --> 00:30:01.842
Wiper stalk
is armed, sir.

358
00:30:11.143 --> 00:30:12.144
<i>Sorry.</i>

359
00:30:12.603 --> 00:30:14.897
<i>Terribly sorry.
We do apologize.</i>

360
00:30:15.022 --> 00:30:17.191
<i>Stop it, Bough,
you'll only encourage them.</i>

361
00:30:32.707 --> 00:30:35.376
What are we gonna do now, sir?
Patience, Bough.

362
00:30:35.918 --> 00:30:38.838
Driving like that, her battery
will be dead any moment.

363
00:30:38.963 --> 00:30:42.216
And she'll roll
to a humiliating stop.

364
00:31:01.485 --> 00:31:05.072
Bough, it is your job to keep
an eye on the fuel gauge.

365
00:31:12.747 --> 00:31:14.915
Very impressive driving, Mr...

366
00:31:16.625 --> 00:31:17.710
Golightly.

367
00:31:18.753 --> 00:31:20.880
Basil Golightly.

368
00:31:23.257 --> 00:31:25.885
And you're rather useful
yourself, Miss...

369
00:31:26.552 --> 00:31:29.597
Bhuletova. Ophelia Bhuletova.

370
00:31:29.764 --> 00:31:31.015
Hmm.

371
00:31:31.098 --> 00:31:32.850
And this is...

372
00:31:33.225 --> 00:31:34.226
Colin.

373
00:31:35.853 --> 00:31:38.022
I thought we were
using fake names.

374
00:31:38.939 --> 00:31:40.691
That is a fake name.

375
00:31:43.527 --> 00:31:44.862
Oh, right.

376
00:31:46.864 --> 00:31:48.741
Yes, this is Colin,

377
00:31:49.992 --> 00:31:51.118
and I'm...

378
00:31:55.289 --> 00:31:56.415
"Dasil."

379
00:31:56.874 --> 00:31:57.875
Dasil.

380
00:31:58.292 --> 00:31:59.293
Basil.

381
00:32:00.544 --> 00:32:02.755
Well, Basil,

382
00:32:03.380 --> 00:32:04.965
maybe there is a simpler way
of doing this.

383
00:32:05.758 --> 00:32:07.176
Over a drink perhaps?

384
00:32:07.259 --> 00:32:09.637
Well, that would be lovely.

385
00:32:09.720 --> 00:32:14.391
Shall we say the bar at the Hotel
de Paris in Cagnes-sur-Mer? 8:00?

386
00:32:14.475 --> 00:32:16.560
Mmm. It's a date.

387
00:32:21.941 --> 00:32:22.942
Well,

388
00:32:23.526 --> 00:32:27.696
I think my "running out of
fuel" ruse worked pretty well.

389
00:32:28.114 --> 00:32:29.323
Mmm.

390
00:32:33.077 --> 00:32:34.161
What?

391
00:32:34.328 --> 00:32:36.705
Er, junior doctors. They've
confirmed they are going on strike

392
00:32:36.789 --> 00:32:38.582
and the tube drivers
are coming out in support.

393
00:32:38.666 --> 00:32:41.502
Oh, God. Leader of the Opposition,
has he come round from his heart surgery?

394
00:32:41.585 --> 00:32:42.628
Yes, Prime Minister.

395
00:32:42.711 --> 00:32:45.840
Oh, Jesus Christ, when will something
go right for me? What do you want?

396
00:32:46.632 --> 00:32:48.676
They've hit us again,
Prime Minister.

397
00:32:49.218 --> 00:32:51.720
Huh? Hacked into the
Central Traffic Control System.

398
00:32:52.012 --> 00:32:55.432
Yes, they've turned every
traffic light in London to red.

399
00:32:58.060 --> 00:32:59.687
Where's my bloody drink?

400
00:33:00.437 --> 00:33:02.815
You've got to be joking?
Vodka tonic, no ice, no tonic.

401
00:33:02.898 --> 00:33:05.442
Yes, ma'am. Oh, and
Mr. Volta has arrived, ma'am.

402
00:33:09.947 --> 00:33:12.575
Mr. Volta,
welcome to Downing Street.

403
00:33:12.700 --> 00:33:15.786
I have read so much
about this wonderful building.

404
00:33:15.911 --> 00:33:19.415
Is this the stone triple staircase
designed by William Kent?

405
00:33:19.540 --> 00:33:22.710
Um, yes, it probably is.
I can't swear to it.

406
00:33:22.835 --> 00:33:25.379
- Can we do a quick...
<i>- Needs Photoshop.</i>

407
00:33:25.462 --> 00:33:27.965
Oh!
This way. Hmm.

408
00:33:28.090 --> 00:33:29.884
I am horribly late,
I do apologize.

409
00:33:30.009 --> 00:33:32.803
It's the traffic, it's the one
thing I don't love about London.

410
00:33:32.928 --> 00:33:35.347
Yes, well, I must admit
we are having a slight problem

411
00:33:35.431 --> 00:33:37.349
with the lights at the moment.
Nothing major.

412
00:33:37.474 --> 00:33:40.477
If you wanted, I could take a
look? It is kind of what I do.

413
00:33:40.561 --> 00:33:43.189
I think it's actually a little
bit more complex than...

414
00:33:43.314 --> 00:33:46.692
Xander, get a web address for
London's traffic control center.

415
00:33:47.359 --> 00:33:51.071
<i>Here is the login page,
